===Etymology 1===
In some senses, from {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|flasshen|lang=enm}}, a variant of {{term|flasken|lang=enm}}, {{m|enm|flaskien||to sprinkle, splash}}, which was likely of imitative origin; in other senses probably of {{etyl|gmq|en}} origin akin to Swedish dialectal {{m|sv|flasa||to burn brightly, blaze}}, related to {{m|en|flare}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|es}}

# To [[brief]]ly [[illuminate]] a [[scene]].
#: {{ux|en|He '''flashed''' the light at the water, trying to see what made the noise.}}
# To [[blink]]; to [[shine]] or [[illuminate]] [[intermittent]]ly.
#: {{ux|en|The light '''flashed''' on and off.}}
#* {{RQ:Chmbrs YngrSt|V}}
#*: Breezes blowing from beds of iris quickened her breath with their perfume; she saw the tufted lilacs sway in the wind, and the streamers of mauve-tinted wistaria swinging, all a-glisten with golden bees; she saw a crimson cardinal winging through the foliage, and amorous tanagers '''flashing''' like scarlet flames athwart the pines.
# To be [[visible]] briefly.
#: {{ux|en|The scenery '''flashed''' by quickly.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1918|author={{w|W. B. Maxwell}}|chapter=5
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the Lamp]
|passage=Here, in the transept and choir, where the service was being held, one was conscious every moment of an increasing brightness; colours glowing vividly beneath the circular chandeliers, and the rows of small lights on the choristers' desks '''flashed''' and sparkled in front of the boys' faces, deep linen collars, and red neckbands.}}
# To make visible briefly.
#: {{ux|en|A number will be '''flashed''' on the screen.}}
#: {{ux|en|The special agents '''flashed''' their badges as they entered the building.}}
# {{lb|en|figurative}} To break forth like a sudden flood of light; to show a momentary brilliance.
#* {{w|Thomas Talfourd}} (1795–1854)
#*: names which have '''flashed''' and thundered as the watch words of unnumbered struggles
#* {{w|Matthew Arnold}} (1822-1888)
#*: The object is made to '''flash''' upon the eye of the mind.
#* {{w|Alfred, Lord Tennyson|Alfred Tennyson}} (1809-1892)
#*: A thought '''flashed''' through me, which I clothed in act.
# To [[flaunt]]; to [[display]] in a showy manner.
#: {{ux|en|He '''flashed''' a wad of hundred-dollar bills.}}
# To [[communicate]] quickly.
#: {{ux|en|The news services '''flashed''' the news about the end of the war to all corners of the globe.}}
#: {{ux|en|to '''flash''' a message along the telephone wires;&emsp; to '''flash''' conviction on the mind}}
# {{lb|en|computing}} To write to the [[memory]] of an updatable component such as a [[BIOS]] chip or games cartridge.
# {{lb|en|ambitransitive|informal}} To briefly, and in most cases inadvertently, expose one's [[naked]] [[body]] or [[underwear]], or part of it, in [[public]]. {{qualifier|Contrast ''[[streak]]''.}}
#: {{ux|en|Her skirt was so short that she '''flashed''' her underpants as she was getting out of her car.}}
# {{lb|en|[[metallurgy]]}} To release the [[pressure]] from a pressurized [[vessel]].
# {{lb|en|[[juggling]]}} To perform a [[#Noun|flash]].
# To [[move]], or cause to move, [[suddenly]]
#: {{ux|en|'''Flash''' forward to the present day.}}
#* {{quote-news|year=2011|date=January 11|author=Jonathan Stevenson|work=BBC
|title=[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/league_cup/9354485.stm West Ham 2-1 Birmingham]
|passage=But they survived some real pressure as David Murphy '''flashed''' a header inches wide of Rob Green's right-hand post{{nb...}}.}}
# {{lb|en|glassmaking}} To cover with a thin layer, as objects of glass with glass of a different colour.
# To trick up in a showy manner.
#* {{w|Antony Brewer}} (fl.1655)
#*: Limning and '''flashing''' it with various dyes.
# To strike and throw up large bodies of water from the surface; to splash.
#* {{w|Edmund Spenser}} (c.1552–1599)
#*: He rudely '''flashed''' the waves about.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[telephone]] a person, only allowing the phone to ring once, in order to request a call back.
#: {{ux|en|Susan '''flashed''' Jessica, and then Jessica called her back, because Susan didn't have enough credit on her phone to make the call.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|of liquid}} To [[evaporate]] suddenly. See {{w|Flash evaporation}}.
# {{lb|en|transitive|climbing}} To climb (a route) successfully on the first attempt.

